Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1230–":"1230–Deceased","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1255–1281":"1255–1281","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1453":"1453","1254":"1254","before 1230":"before 1230","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Connan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Manx: variant of   Cannon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Canan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aileen, Murphy, Paddy.","Irish: variant of   Cannan  ."]},{"name":"Cannon","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Canann</b> or <b>Ó Canáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cano</i> or <i>Canán</i>’. Occasionally, and in the Isle of Man, the surname derives from <i>Mac Canann</i> ‘son of <i>Cano</i> or <i>Canán</i>’, which in Ireland was Anglicized   McCann   or   McConnon  . See also   Connon  . The personal name is from Gaelic <i>cano</i> ‘wolf cub’, of which <i>Canán</i> is a diminutive. In Ulster Cannon may also be shortened from <b>Ó Canannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Canannán’</i>, a pet form (double diminutive) of the personal name. This was a cheiftan family in Donegal, and the name was particularly common there.","English: from Middle English <i>canun</i> ‘canon’ (Old Norman French <i>canonie</i>, <i>canoine</i>, from Late Latin <i>canonicus</i>). In medieval England this term denoted a clergyman living with others in a clergy house; the surname is mostly an occupational name for a servant in a house of canons, although it could also be a nickname or even a patronymic.","French: variant of   Canon  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: Bitter; Marion is the French form."],"variants":[{"name":"Marion","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."]},{"name":"Marcia","meanings":["Often used as a feminine equivalent of   Mark  , but in fact a feminine form of <i>Marcius</i>, itself a derivative of   Marcus .  One  St Marcia  is commemorated in a group with Felix, Luciolus, Fortunatus, and others; another with Zenais, Cyria, and Valeria; and a third with Ariston, Crescentian, Eutychian, Urban, Vitalis, Justus, Felicissimus, Felix, and Symphorosa. None is individually very famous."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":98,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":107,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mary Connan was born in 1230, in Cheadle, Staffordshire, England as the daughter of Robert Coventry and Mrs Robert Coventry. She married Edmund Farnell in 1254, in Cheadle, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in Cheadle, Cheshire, England."},"et":{"1230–":"1230–Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1255–1281":"1255–1281","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1453":"1453","1254":"1254","before 1230":"enne 1230","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, England":"Cheadle, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Cheadle, Cheshire, England":"Cheadle, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1230–":"1230–Kuollut","1230–Female":"1230–Kuollut","1235–1260":"1235–1260","1255–1281":"1255–1281","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1230":"1230","1260":"1260","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1453":"1453","1254":"1254","before 1230":"ennen vuotta 1230","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Cheadle, Cheshire, Staffordshire, E